				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Does this mean that if C (&quot;length counter disable/linear counter control&quot;) is clear, then both the length counter and the linear counter will be counting down, while C being set means they're both halted? (In that case, calling it something like &quot;length counter halt/linear counter halt&quot; might be clearer.)</div><br />No. The control flag being clear clears the halt flag, but the control flag being set doesn't affect the halt flag. It doesn't directly affect linear counter operation, only the halt flag.<br /><br />The halt flag in the linear counter stops the counter from decrementing when it's set. And yes, it also affects when the linear counter is reloaded.<br /><br />I probably chose the name &quot;halt&quot; because it's one word. It's really a mode flag, telling whether the linear counter is reloaded or decremented on linear clocks. We could call it a mode flag, with the two modes named:<br /><br />* <em>linear mode</em> can be in one of two states: <em>reloading</em> or <em>counting</em>.<br />* Writing to $400B sets <em>linear mode</em> to <em>reloading</em>.<br />* When the frame counter generates a linear counter clock, the following actions occur in order:<br />1. If <em>linear mode</em> = <em>reloading</em>, linear counter is reloaded with counter reload value from $4008.<br />   If <em>linear mode</em> = <em>counting</em> and linear counter &gt; 0, linear counter is decremented.<br />2. If bit 7 of $4008 is clear, <em>linear mode</em> is set to <em>counting</em>.<br /><br />Bring on critique round two and let's refine this more!</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

